      "content": "```python\ndef main():\n    n, m = 1000000, 2000000\n    fa = [0] * (n + 1)\n    for u, v in enumerate(map(int, input().split())):\n        fa[v] = u\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        if fa[i] == 0:\n            cnt = 0\n            j = i\n            while fa[j] != 0:\n                cnt += 1\n                fa[j] = 0\n                j = fa[j] + 1\n            print(cnt, end=' ')\n    print()\n\nmain()\n```\nThis code doesn't store all the edges in memory at once, which should help with the memory usage. Instead, it processes the edges one by one and updates the DSU as it goes. The `fa` array is used to keep track of the parent of each node, and the `cnt` variable is used to count the number of nodes in each connected component.\n\nThis code should be able to pass the memory limit, but keep in mind that it's not the most efficient solution. It has a time complexity of O(m), which is acceptable for this problem",
